In the architecture you described, authentication is likely handled at the API Gateway layer (Apigee) rather than within the AKS networking layer or the microservice itself.
This is a common "Sidecar" or "Gateway" offloading pattern where the backend service remains "unaware" of security logic to keep it lightweight and focused on business logic.

1. The Role of Apigee (The Entry Point)
Since your other project contains Apigee proxies and policies (XML/JSON), Apigee acts as the security enforcement point.
When you send an OAuth token in your test environment,the flow typically looks like this:
OAuth Verification: The Apigee proxy contains an OAuthV2 policy. 
When a request hits the proxy with a Header: Authorization Bearer <token>, Apigee intercepts it, validates the token against its own data store (or an external Identity Provider), and extracts the associated developer metadata.
Credential Injection: Once validated, Apigee uses the username and password (stored in your Ansible properties) to perform a "Service Callout" or to fulfill a "Basic Auth" policy.
It injects these credentials into the header of the request before forwarding it to your backend.

2. Why your Service has "No Trace" of Auth
Your backend service (running in AKS) likely expects Basic Authentication or a specific header that Apigee provides. 
Because Apigee handles the translation from OAuth (Public-facing) to Basic Auth (Internal-facing), the microservice code doesn't need to know how to validate OAuth tokens. 
It simply trusts the request because it comes from the Apigee IP range or contains the correct internal credentials.

3. Is it using AKS Networking?
While AKS networking (like a LoadBalancer or Ingress Controller) is used to physically route the traffic into the cluster, it is not likely responsible for the authentication logic you are seeing.
AKS Networking's Role: It ensures that the request from Apigee reaches the correct Pod.
Apigee’s Role: It ensures the user is "who they say they are" via OAuth and translates that into the credentials your service expects.
How to verify this in your Test Environment
To confirm this flow, you can check the following in your Apigee project:
Check the Proxy Flow: Look for a <Step> in the XML files that references a VerifyAccessToken policy. This confirms OAuth is being checked.
Look for AssignMessage: Look for a policy in the XML that uses the Ansible-provided apigee.username. It will likely look like this:

<AssignMessage name="AddAuthHeader">
   <Set>
      <Headers>
         <Header name="Authorization">{private.encoded_credentials}</Header>
      </Headers>
   </Set>
</AssignMessage>
Target Endpoint: Check the TargetEndpoint configuration in the proxy. 
          It will point to the internal load balancer IP or the DNS name of your service running in AKS.
Note on Security: In this setup, it is crucial that your AKS service is not exposed to the public internet. 
It should only accept traffic originating from Apigee's IP addresses to prevent someone from bypassing the OAuth layer and hitting your service directly with the internal credentials.


The mongo database needs to be upgraded to the version 7.
For this, the mongo drivers in the middleware services needs to be updated to mongo version 5.3.1

Compatibility Overview:
The MongoDB Java/Node.js Driver 5.3.x is fully compatible with MongoDB 7.0.
In fact, the 5.x driver line is the recommended path for users moving toward MongoDB 7.0 and 8.0.

Component               Target Version          Compatibility Notes
MongoDB Server          7.0                     Supports new features like Queryable Encryption (GA) and Vector Search.
MongoDB Driver          5.3.1                  Minimum requirement for several 7.0 features; supports JDK 17+ (for Java).
Spring Data (if used)   2024.1 (4.4.x)        "If your middleware uses Spring Data MongoDB, version 4.4.x or higher is required for driver 5.2+."

Critical Changes in Driver 5.3.1
When moving to version 5.3.1 from older versions (like 4.x), keep an eye on these mechanical changes:
Dropped Support for Server 4.0: Driver 5.3 officially raises the minimum supported server version to 4.2. 
        Since you are moving to 7.0, this won't impact your connection to the new DB, but it means you cannot use this driver to connect to very old legacy clusters during a transition.
Vector Search & BinaryVector: If your middleware handles AI or similarity search, 5.3.1 introduces the BinaryVector class. 
        This provides more efficient storage for vector data compared to standard lists.
Connection Pool Fairness: Version 5.3.1 removes "explicit fairness" from the connection pool. 
        This generally improves throughput for high-concurrency microservices (like those in AKS), though you might see a slight increase in "tail latency" (p99) in very specific scenarios.

New Write Options: You can now use a sort option within updateOne() and replaceOne() operations, which wasn't possible in older driver versions.
